      "side": 1,
      "message": "GetSysInfoState and CollectSysInfo may look confusing.\nAlthough these names are already defined in the jsonprotocol, I think it\u0027s better to have names that differentiate each other.\n- SysInfoState: logs and crash files location/size\n- (Collect)SysInfo: LogDir and CrashDir\n\nWhat are the principle difference? (just the timings when these are collected?)\n",
      "revId": "b6078a60ed309342a3501c07694f3912db362183",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "12d248f2_71e05ba4",
        "filename": "/PATCHSET_LEVEL",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 0,
      "author": {
        "id": 1118346
      },
      "writtenOn": "2021-05-27T08:27:08Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "The idea is like this:\n\n\"system info\" is a collection of system logs, e.g. /var/log/messages. So CollectSysInfo means to pull those log files. However we\u0027re interested in diff of those files between run start and run end, so we define \"state of system info\", a snapshot of system log files. This is called SysInfoState and represented as file sizes. GetSysInfoState is a method to obtain a snapshot.\n\nDoes this explanation make sense?",
      "parentUuid": "5f8ffb39_2ba74ea5",
      "revId": "b6078a60ed309342a3501c07694f3912db362183",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba"
    },
